law soft-deletes/tombstones (deleted_at? status? grace window?) and ensures the delete is idempotent + audited; how supersession links old->new; whether relations/edges carry provenance (generated vs manual) so a re-promotion does not duplicate; how (if at all) it validates a relationship before persisting it.\n\n  Line 15: CONCRETE designs: (004) a causal-edge tombstone lifecycle for SQLite — the edge-state columns, the tombstone-before-hard-delete algorithm, idempotent re-run; (005) a deterministic metadata-edge promotion guard — what \"validated\" means, how provenance (generated-by=promoter vs manual) prevents duplicate promotion.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/prompts/iteration-094.md:\n  Line 3: TARGET: caura-memclaw (multi-tenant, Postgres/pgvector). CONSUMER: Spec Kit Memory (LOCAL single-user, SQLite + vector store) — 027/008 = shadow-first learning-feedback reducers. MemClaw is Apache-2.0 — design inspiration only.\n\n  Line 8: YOUR ANGLE (iteration 094): DEEP self-improving loop internals -> design 027/008. Verify with exact file:line: the outcome data model + weight-application transaction; the rule-synthesis confidence gate; the insight hallucination-gating + supersession; how feedback reaches ranking/retention. Then answer the OPEN QUESTIONS from 084: (1) durable outcome event record vs implicit telemetry; (2) should generated rules be shadow/probation before entering recall; (3) does single-agent insight mining have enough signal (which modes: failures/stale/patterns yes, divergence no); (4) should feedback alter importance-tier, FSRS decay schedule, retrieval score, retention eligibility — or which subset; (5) asymmetric damping risk (failures lower weight faster than successes raise — risk of losing rare-but-correct memories in a SMALL local corpus).\n\n  Line 15: A CONCRETE shadow-first reducer design for a single-agent local store: the outcome-event record (SQLite shape), the shadow ledger, the promotion gate (what evidence promotes a shadow signal to active), and exactly which target it mutates (tier vs FSRS decay vs score vs retention) with SYMMETRIC/soft damping to protect rare-but-correct memories. Tie to Spec Kit's existing FSRS decay + importance tiers + constitutional protection.\n\n  Line 22: DELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"094\",\"focus\":\"DEEP self-improving loop -> 027/008 shadow-first reducer design\",\"findingsCount\":<int>,\"newInfoRatio\":<0.0-1.0>,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: ...\",\"DEFER: ...\"],\"sources\":[\"path:line\"]}\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-092.md:\n  Line 16: Regression scaffolding covers memory-quality-adjacent properties: recall behavior and LLM-brief cost control (`tests/test_mcp_recall.py:1`, `tests/test_mcp_recall.py:3`, `tests/test_mcp_recall.py:143`, `tests/test_mcp_recall.py:189`), insight diagnostics for stale memories, failures, patterns, persistence, supersession ordering, and hallucinated-ID filtering (`tests/test_insights_service.py:1`, `tests/test_insights_service.py:3`, `tests/test_insights_service.py:310`, `tests/test_insights_service.py:371`, `tests/test_insights_service.py:400`, `tests/test_insights_service.py:443`, `tests/test_insights_service.py:490`, `tests/test_insights_service.py:901`), evolve/outcome feedback weight math (`tests/test_evolve_service.py:1`, `tests/test_evolve_service.py:3`, `tests/test_evolve_service.py:62`, `tests/test_evolve_service.py:81`), visibility/security isolation (`tests/test_visibility_scoping.py:1`, `tests/test_visibility_scoping.py:7`, `tests/test_security_tenant_isolation.py:1`, `tests/test_security_tenant_isolation.py:64`), and health/dependency gates (`tests/test_health_gate.py:1`, `tests/test_health_gate.py:3`, `tests/test_health_gate.py:30`, `tests/test_health_gate.py:97`).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-090.md:\n  Line 10: - MemClaw’s core token-efficiency claim is recall-by-slice, not full transcript replay: “recall returns the relevant slice, not the full transcript,” with 96-98% token savings versus full context. Evidence: `docs/performance.md:23-31`, `README.md:283-289`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-088.md:\n  Line 29: 4. **Claim** · Define delivery semantics around idempotency, not exactly-once. **Evidence** · EventBus requires idempotent handlers under at-least-once delivery and recommends `event_id` for dedup (`common/events/base.py:73`); Pub/Sub dispatch nacks any handler failure, redelivering the event to all handlers (`common/events/pubsub.py:639`). Embed/enrich handlers are designed as safe write-after-write PATCHes (`core-worker/src/core_worker/consumer.py:25`, `core-worker/src/core_worker/clients/storage_client.py:473`). **Maps-to** · 027/006. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Local in-process retries can still duplicate work unless job identity and derived-output writes are guarded. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit does not need distributed at-least-once transport, but it should still assume crashes/retries can replay jobs and make handlers deterministic or deduped by row id + content hash + target model.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-086.md:\n  Line 37: **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit already has causal edges and tombstones; the transferable part is requiring provenance memory/spec-doc evidence and idempotent natural keys for relationship promotion.\n\n  Line 45: **Why it transfers (or not)** · Strongly transfers because 027/005 is already deterministic; use this as a pattern for validating parent/child/frontmatter entity claims before edge promotion.\n\n  Line 83: Would a subject-entity preflight guard reduce false causal promotions, similar to MemClaw’s “both subject IDs present and different means skip” rule? Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/subject_preflight.py:3`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/subject_preflight.py:24`.\n\n  Line 85: DELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"086\",\"focus\":\"entity / relationship / graph modeling\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.78,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: separate entity relationship side-channel from causal memory edges\",\"ADOPT: deterministic validation guards before metadata-edge promotion\",\"ADAPT: bounded entity graph recall boost with fallbacks\",\"DEFER: co-occurrence inferred relations without tombstone/provenance semantics\"],\"sources\":[\"common/models/entity.py:27\",\"common/models/memory.py:80\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:15\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:99\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2709\"]}\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-084.md:\n  Line 25: 8. **Insight gating.** Insight generation excludes prior `insight` memories from source queries to avoid insight-on-insight feedback loops; hallucinated `related_memory_ids` are dropped unless they were actually shown to the LLM; prior active insights for the same focus/scope/fleet are moved to `outdated` before new ones persist, and restored if all new persists fail. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py:283-320`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py:926-1008`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py:706-780`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py:893-913`.\n\n  Line 27: 9. **System-authored feedback types are protected.** `outcome`, `rule`, and `insight` are server-reserved memory types. Agents cannot write them directly through public REST/MCP write paths, preventing forged learning signals. Evidence: `common/enrichment/constants.py:70-91`, `common/enrichment/constants.py:97-110`, `core-api/src/core_api/routes/memories.py:101-131`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:281-310`.\n\n  Line 41: 1. **Claim** · Outcome feedback can transfer to a single-agent local store if treated as attribution-weighted ranking/retention evidence, not fleet propagation.\n\n  Line 49: 2. **Claim** · Failure-to-rule synthesis should be shadow-first in Spec Kit, not immediately authoritative.\n\n  Line 57: 3. **Claim** · Reserve system-generated feedback artifact types separately from user-authored memories.\n\n  Line 63:    **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit’s 027/008 reducers need trustworthy feedback provenance even with one user; separating human notes from reducer-emitted learning records prevents feedback poisoning.\n\n  Line 99: 3. Decide whether Spec Kit should let generated “rules” enter normal recall immediately, or keep them in a shadow/probation tier until repeated validation.\n\n  Line 103: 5. Compare MemClaw’s direct weight mutation with Spec Kit’s FSRS decay and importance tiers: should feedback alter tier, decay schedule, retrieval score, retention eligibility, or all four?\n\n  Line 107: DELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"084\",\"focus\":\"self-improving memory / outcome propagation loop\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.86,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: outcome feedback can improve single-agent future recall when scoped to attribution-weighted ranking/retention, not fleet propagation\",\"REJECT: fleet trust/scoping and cross-agent propagation machinery should not be imported into local single-user Spec Kit\"],\"sources\":[\"README.md:265\",\"docs/performance.md:42\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py:683\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py:1011\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:973\"]}\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-083.md:\n  Line 25: 1. **Claim** · ADAPT trust tiers into provenance trust, not access-control trust. **Evidence** · MemClaw trust levels gate fleet powers (`docs/integration-without-plugin.md:167`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:171`) and enforcement lives in fleet read/write/delete gates (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet: `provenance-trust-weighting-for-derived-memory`. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Over-importing authz semantics would add fake multi-agent complexity to a single-user store. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The transferable concept is “not all memories deserve equal authority.” Spec Kit already has importance tiers and constitutional always-surface memories; the missing analog is trust weighting for source/provenance, e.g. human-authored > validated automated > shadow-derived > stale/low-confidence.\n\n  Line 27: 2. **Claim** · ADAPT append-only audit for automated memory mutations. **Evidence** · MemClaw’s settings path writes a flat diff audit row after updates (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:801`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:824`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846`), and generic audit events include tenant, agent, action, resource, and detail (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:50`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:56`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet: `automated-mutation-audit-trail`. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A full fleet audit queue is unnecessary and can become operational noise. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user Spec Kit does not need forensic tenant accounting, but it does need explainability for self-maintaining index changes, shadow feedback promotions, tier changes, bulk deletes, retention sweeps, and causal-edge backfills.\n\n  Line 29: 3. **Claim** · REJECT agent/fleet/cross-tenant scope machinery; keep only a local default-deny analog for sensitive auto-derived state. **Evidence** · MemClaw scopes are explicitly fleet concepts (`static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:69`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:70`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:72`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:73`), and query filters prevent `scope_agent` leaks across callers (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:136`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:149`). **Maps-to** · 027 child or new sub-packet: `local-visibility-for-ephemeral-derived-state`. **Verdict** · REJECT fleet mechanism / ADAPT concept. **Risk** · If copied directly, Spec Kit would gain meaningless “agents/fleets” and confuse retrieval policy. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · There is no cross-team leak risk in a local single-user database. The only useful analog is default-deny surfacing for draft, shadow, quarantined, or low-confidence derived memories until promoted.\n\n  Line 54: 4. Should shadow-first feedback reducers write an audit/event log before promotion, or is current telemetry sufficient?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-082.md:\n  Line 27: - **Claim** · Keep retrieval diagnostics as first-class output for tuning, not just logs. **Evidence** · Diagnostic mode widens candidate capture and records all candidates, search params, retrieval strategy, and original top_k (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/execute_scored_search.py:52`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:3084`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:3087`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/recall_service.py:205`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/recall_service.py:210`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet; Spec Kit already has shadow-first learning-feedback reducers and rich MCP search surfaces. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Diagnostic payloads can become token-expensive if exposed by default. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user local systems benefit from transparent “why this result” traces, but should keep them opt-in/debug-profile only.\n\n  Line 36: - Do not copy per-agent retrieval profiles literally. MemClaw advertises per-agent retrieval tuning for fleets (`README.md:267`, `README.md:269`), while Spec Kit is single-user/local; any equivalent should be a local profile or shadow-learned configuration, not agent governance.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-081.md:\n  Line 12: Idempotency is split into response-level replay and row-level bulk retry safety. Single writes can use `Idempotency-Key` from a header or metadata fallback (`core-api/src/core_api/routes/memories.py:868`, `core-api/src/core_api/routes/memories.py:880`, `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/idempotency.py:54`). The idempotency row stores `(tenant_id, idempotency_key)`, request hash, response body, status code, expiry, and `is_pending` (`common/models/idempotency.py:30`, `common/models/idempotency.py:42`, `common/models/idempotency.py:53`). Reusing a key with a different body is a 422 conflict (`core-api/src/core_api/middleware/idempotency.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/idempotency.py:198`). Concurrent same-key requests are handled by claim-then-poll with a pending sentinel (`core-api/src/core_api/middleware/idempotency.py:158`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4566`). Bulk writes require `X-Bulk-Attempt-Id`; per-item ids become `f\"{attempt_id}:{index}\"`, and retries resolve as `duplicate_attempt` instead of duplicating (`README.md:587`, `core-api/src/core_api/routes/memories.py:991`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:998`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1123`). Storage enforces that with a partial unique index on `(tenant_id, COALESCE(fleet_id,''), client_request_id)` and `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING`, then re-reads canonical ids for conflicted rows (`common/models/memory.py:96`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:282`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:344`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:376`).\n\n  Line 19: - **Claim** · Add a local idempotency receipt table for `memory_save` / `memory_update` keyed by caller-supplied or server-derived operation id plus request hash. **Evidence** · MemClaw stores `(tenant_id, idempotency_key)` with request hash, response body, status, expiry, and pending state (`common/models/idempotency.py:30`, `common/models/idempotency.py:42`, `common/models/idempotency.py:53`), rejects same-key different-body conflicts (`core-api/src/core_api/middleware/idempotency.py:198`), and uses claim/poll to close same-key races (`core-api/src/core_api/middleware/idempotency.py:158`). **Maps-to** · 027 child 006 write-path-reconciliation. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · MED. **Confidence** · 0.86. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The single-user SQLite store does not need tenant scoping or HTTP replay semantics, but it does need retry-safe saves after tool crashes, timeouts, or duplicate MCP calls.\n\n  Line 21: - **Claim** · Preserve automated enrichment as merge-only/default-fill unless the human explicitly asks for replacement. **Evidence** · MemClaw’s enrichment step says agent-provided values win (`core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/write/merge_enrichment_fields.py:29`), deferred enrichment carries `agent_provided_fields` so worker redelivery cannot overwrite explicit values (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:1656`), and metadata PATCH defaults to merge while requiring explicit replace for clear/overwrite (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2359`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2385`). **Maps-to** · 027 child 002 write-safety and 006 write-path-reconciliation. **Verdict** · ADOPT. **Risk** · LOW. **Confidence** · 0.93. **Why it transfers (or not)** · This directly fits Spec Kit Memory’s need to protect constitutional/manual records from generated summaries, trigger suggestions, confidence updates, and feedback reducers.\n\n  Line 41: Should Spec Kit Memory add a first-class `source_kind` enum such as `human`, `agent`, `system`, `import`, `feedback_reducer`, and use it in write gates?\n\n  Line 49: Should automatic feedback reducers be forbidden from changing constitutional/critical rows directly, or allowed only to propose pending patches?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/prompts/iteration-084.md:\n  Line 6: - CONSUMER: \"Spec Kit Memory\" — LOCAL, SINGLE-USER store. SQLite + vector store; importance tiers; causal edges; FSRS decay; self-maintaining index; **shadow-first learning-feedback reducers (027 child 008)** that learn from outcomes to adjust ranking/retention; 37-tool MCP. This angle is the HIGHEST-VALUE overlap: 027/008 is exactly a \"learn from feedback to improve memory\" system.\n\n  Line 8: CRITICAL JUDGMENT RULE: MemClaw's self-improvement is CROSS-AGENT (\"agent #17's mistake prevents agents #1-40 repeating it\"). Spec Kit has ONE user/agent — there is no fleet to propagate to. The hard question: does MemClaw's outcome->insight loop have ANY single-agent analog (e.g., one agent's outcomes improving its OWN future recall/ranking/retention over time)? Distinguish the cross-agent propagation (likely negative knowledge) from the outcome-capture + insight-derivation + shadow-gating MECHANISM (potentially transferable to 027/008). Be concrete and skeptical.\n\n  Line 11: Read these entry points first, follow imports WITHIN caura-memclaw only (cap ~15 files). Grep for: \"evolve\", \"insight\", \"outcome\", \"feedback\", \"propagat\", \"learn\", \"review\", \"analysis_report\".\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/prompts/iteration-083.md:\n  Line 6: - CONSUMER: \"Spec Kit Memory\" — LOCAL, SINGLE-USER, SINGLE-TENANT store. SQLite index + vector store (ollama nomic 768d); importance tiers (constitutional > critical > important > normal > temporary); causal edges; FSRS decay; self-maintaining index; shadow-first feedback reducers; 37-tool MCP. NOTE: Spec Kit ALREADY has importance tiers and \"constitutional\" always-surface memories. Refined under packet 027.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/prompts/iteration-082.md:\n  Line 6: - CONSUMER (who the teachings are FOR): \"Spec Kit Memory\" — a LOCAL, SINGLE-USER, SINGLE-TENANT continuity/memory store. SQLite index + SEPARATE vector store (ollama nomic 768-dim); hybrid lexical + semantic trigger matching; importance tiers (constitutional > critical > important > normal > temporary); causal edges (tombstone lifecycle); FSRS decay + co-activation; self-maintaining incremental index; shadow-first learning-feedback reducers; 37-tool MCP surface. Refined under packet 027 (children 002-008 as listed in the strategy).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/prompts/iteration-081.md:\n  Line 6: - CONSUMER (who the teachings are FOR): \"Spec Kit Memory\" — a LOCAL, SINGLE-USER, SINGLE-TENANT continuity/memory store for one developer's AI coding workflow. Architecture: SQLite index file + a SEPARATE vector store (ollama nomic, 768-dim); hybrid lexical + semantic trigger matching; importance tiers (constitutional > critical > important > normal > temporary); causal edges between memories (with tombstone lifecycle); FSRS-style decay + co-activation; a self-maintaining incremental index; shadow-first learning-feedback reducers; a 37-tool MCP surface (memory_save / memory_search / memory_context / memory_causal_link / etc.). Refined under packet 027, children: 002 write-safety, 003 incremental-index, 004 causal-edge-tombstones, 005 metadata-edge-promoter, 006 write-path-reconciliation, 007 semantic-trigger-fallback, 008 learning-feedback-reducers.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/deep-research-strategy.md:\n  Line 12: **Consumer:** Spec Kit Memory — LOCAL single-user/single-tenant store (SQLite index + vector store, ollama nomic 768d); semantic+lexical triggers; importance tiers; causal edges; FSRS decay/co-activation; self-maintaining incremental index; shadow-first learning-feedback reducers; 37-tool MCP surface.\n\n  Line 41: - [ ] 094 DEEP self-improving loop internals: evolve->insights data model, shadow/active gating -> 027/008\n\n  Line 47: - [ ] 098 ADVERSARIAL refute self-improving/feedback teachings (fleet outcome-propagation has no single-user analog?)\n\n  Line 49: - [ ] 100 ADVERSARIAL refute MCP-surface/perf/benchmark teachings + finalize negative-knowledge ledger\n","metadata":{"matches":94,"truncated":false},"title":"shadow|ledger|promotion|default-off|DEFAULT-OFF|SHADOW-FIRST|feedback|replay|per-consumer","time":{"start":1780729373992,"end":1780729374008}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b64001883977240016a23c61df00481919bc40ac029d4da65"}},"id":"prt_e9bbde526001Kdkroqyn6hpv0p","sessionID":"ses_16443656effeEz6GoJAQaGGpUT","messageID":"msg_e9bbdbc85001TMa67Msoo0Fg1n"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780729374345,"sessionID":"ses_16443656effeEz6GoJAQaGGpUT","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbde687001sOeS9p6aSsK0lU","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"3ed79b54d6b7979e4743e44bca4b1c3193097c33","messageID":"msg_e9bbdbc85001TMa67Msoo0Fg1n","sessionID":"ses_16443656effeEz6GoJAQaGGpUT","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":38223,"input":6047,"output":432,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":31744}},"cost":0}}
